    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
            <p><bibl><ptr target="#cdl-rosamilia2016"/> (ph.)<citedRange/></bibl>, whence
                <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>66.2337</citedRange></bibl>;
                <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>125700</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            <p>Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#cdl-maffre2018"/></bibl>, whence 
            <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/> <citedRange>68.1746</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="0"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="line"><certainty match=".." locus="name"/></gap>
                    <lb n="1"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> <orig><unclear>αδ</unclear></orig> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="divine" ref="#Apollo"><name nymRef="#Ἀπόλλων"><supplied reason="lost">Ἀπόλλω</supplied>νι</name></persName> <w lemma="δεκάτα">δ<unclear>ε</unclear><supplied reason="lost" cert="low">κάταν</supplied></w>
                    <lb n="3"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#_όνισκος"><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><seg part="F">ονίσκου</seg></name></persName> <w lemma="ποιέω">ἐ<supplied reason="lost" cert="low">ποίησεν</supplied></w>.
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> <supplied reason="subaudible">a consacré</supplied> à Apollon au titre de la d<supplied reason="lost" cert="low">îme</supplied>.</p>
            <p><supplied reason="lost">Oeuvre d'Untel</supplied> fils de <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>oniskos.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> <supplied reason="subaudible">dedicated</supplied> to Apollo as a t<supplied reason="lost" cert="low">ithe</supplied>.</p>
            <p><supplied reason="lost">Work of So-and-so</supplied> son of <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>oniskos.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> <supplied reason="subaudible">ha dedicato</supplied> ad Apollo come d<supplied reason="lost" cert="low">ecima</supplied>.</p>
            <p><supplied reason="lost">Opera del tale</supplied> figlio di <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>oniskos.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                      <p>Although very fragmentary, this inscription consists clearly of a dedication with an artist's signature in smaller characters below.</p>
	           <p>At line 2, the restoration was chosen on behalf of its high frequency in Cyrenaean inscriptions. It is associated with an artist's signature 
	            in <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr019000</ref>. At first view it is not quite impossible that the text read <foreign xml:lang="grc"><supplied reason="lost">ἐκ τῶ</supplied>ν ἰδ<supplied reason="lost">ίων</supplied></foreign>
	            'at his own expense', which would be used for honoring a person with a statue. However such formulas occur only later and exclusively for building 
	           or reparing works.</p>
	           <p>At line 3, we restore the most common formula. There also exists at Cyrene at least one instance with <foreign xml:lang="grc">ἔ<supplied reason="lost">ργον</supplied></foreign> (see <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr108400</ref> with the commentary). In the latter case, the ending of genitive would belong to the sculptor's name. In the 
	               preferred reading, the father's name of the sculptor ended with <foreign xml:lang="grc">-ονίσκος</foreign>. No such name is hitherto attested in Cyrene.
	               As no ethnic is mentioned, thie sculptor was plausibly a Cyrenaean.</p>
            </div></body>
    </text>
